\begin_layout Subsection
How is this calculated ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of experiments is done at the level of p-values, thus a
 matrix of p-values per item (rows) and conditions (columns) is the input
 for this analysis.
 The combination is done using the generalized weighted Z-method, to combine
 evidence from independent studies.
 This pooling method was proved to perform well on sparse data and small
 values of significance level.
 The formula of Liptak-Stouffer for pooling evidence from the collection
 of studies uses the inverse-transformation of the standard normal distribution
 on the individual list of p-values:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{comb,g}=\frac{\overset{n_{e}}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\omega_{i}Z_{i,g}}{\sqrt{\overset{n_{e}}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\omega_{i}^{2}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where Z
\begin_inset Formula $_{i,g}$
\end_inset

 is the z-score from the i-th experiment and g-th gen and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the weight assigned to the experiment.
 Weights are averaged by default but the user can provide different weights
 for each experiment.
 Thus, the computed z-score is easily interpreted: values close to 0 indicate
 high significance for this item taking into account all experiments combined.
\end_layout

